sentences: William Orville "Lefty" Frizzell (March 31, 1928 – July 19, 1975) was an American country music singer-songwriter and honky-tonk singer.
He was inducted into the Country Music Hall of Fame in 1982.
After the death of Hank Williams in 1953, Frizzell released many songs that charted in the Top 10 of the Hot Country Songs charts.
His success did not carry on into the 1960s, and after suffering from alcoholism, he died at age 47.
Frizzell's teens were spent singing in nightclubs and radio and talent shows throughout the south.
